image.altText: A sunny image of the grand front gate of Cranbrook private school

props.synopsis: A Cranbrook school teacher who has been on leave following Four Corners revelations has been temporarily banned from teaching in New South Wales schools.

title.children: Cranbrook teacher who allegedly sent graphic emails banned from teaching in NSW schools

image.altText: People wave Palestinian flags in support of resolution.

props.synopsis: Australian Foreign Minister Penny Wong suggests the federal government is contemplating recognising Palestinian statehood, saying international recognition could help "build momentum towards a two-state solution" with Israel.

title.children: 'It undermines Hamas': Wong suggests Australian government considering recognising Palestinian statehood

image.altText: Three different images: A man holding a model of a spine, a woman dancing and a man pointing

props.synopsis: People with chronic pain are suffering infections, shocks and even more pain from a device advertised as safe and effective. There are now calls for them to be recalled following a Four Corners investigation.

title.children: Experts are sounding the alarm about these pain devices. Why are thousands having them implanted each year?

image.altText: A group of people holding Israeli flags.

props.synopsis: Israel's ultra-Orthodox community has always been exempt from mandatory military service but a ruling in the country's highest court has changed everything.

title.children: '200,000 Torah students' are allegedly protecting Israel. Critics say it's time they fought

image.altText: An image of Brittany Higgins next to an image of Bruce Lehrmann.

props.synopsis: The Federal Court has published final submissions made by Brittany Higgins in Bruce Lehrmann's defamation case against Network Ten and journalist Lisa Wilkinson.

title.children: Brittany Higgins gave 'unwavering' account of alleged rape throughout defamation trial: lawyer

image.altText: A composite image of three men, Eddie McGuire, Andrew Dillon and Barry Rigby.

props.synopsis: Independent MP Andrew Wilkie's allegations of rampant illicit drug use in the AFL have rocked the game. Now stakeholders past and present face a divide on what is best for the sport and the players themselves.

title.children: 'You should be named': McGuire wants AFL to toughen code's illicit drugs policy

image.altText: MONA Ladie's Lounge and Kirsha Kaechele and supporters.

props.synopsis: MONA refusing to allow a man to enter its Ladies Lounge was discriminatory, a tribunal has found. The tribunal's deputy president has also called out the behaviour of a group of women for their "performance art" during the hearing in March.

title.children: Tasmania's MONA gallery ordered to permit men inside 'women-only' lounge

image.altText: A thumbnail of Sydney's tolls and a piles of $50 bills.

props.synopsis: In January, the NSW government's toll rebate system came into effect. Claims have opened today. But who's eligible? And how can you actually claim?

title.children: Sydney drivers could be eligible for up to $340 per week in toll relief from today. Find out who qualifies

image.altText: Bruce Lehrmann walking into court.

props.synopsis: A new date has been set for a judgment in the defamation case brought by former Liberal staffer Bruce Lehrmann against Network Ten and Lisa Wilkinson, which was delayed last week when the network successfully applied to bring fresh evidence before the court.

title.children: Judgment in Bruce Lehrmann defamation case to be handed down on Monday

image.altText: Smiling women front a media pack after their human rights court win

props.synopsis: Europe's human rights court has ruled two of three key climate change cases before it are inadmissible, but found in favour of another — a group of Swiss women who say their government's climate fight is "woefully inadequate".

title.children: Swiss women win in human rights court on climate argument, but two separate cases ruled 'inadmissible'

image.altText: A transgender woman walks past photographs outside a court house.

props.synopsis: Social media platform Giggle for Girls is being sued by transgender woman Roxanne Tickle after her access to the women-only app was revoked. The app's owner has denied Ms Tickle is a woman.

title.children: Transgender woman sues women-only social media platform she was excluded from

image.altText: A graphic of a thermometer and the globe indicating rising heat

props.synopsis: As the world continues its spell of hottest months on record, leading climate scientists say there is a margin to the persistent heat which cannot be explained by the effects of known climate drivers and global warming.

title.children: 'Uncharted territory': The world's extreme heat can't be fully explained, and scientists are worried

image.altText: Eva Lawler at an indoor press conference with flags in the background.

props.synopsis: The NT chief minister says the youth curfew in Alice Springs has been a "circuit breaker", leading to a reduction in crime and an increase in the number of families asking for support.

title.children: Alice Springs youth curfew extended by six nights to see out school holidays

image.altText: A wide shot of the front entrance to Casuarina Prison, with two men dressed in blue walking out and trees in the foreground.

props.synopsis: A coronial inquest into WA's first recorded death in youth custody has heard it's not possible to treat detainees lawfully and humanely at Unit 18.WARNING: This story contains the name and image of an Indigenous person who has died.

title.children: Inquest into death of Cleveland Dodd hears humane treatment impossible at notorious Unit 18

image.altText: Two young women with crossed arms look at the camera.

props.synopsis: Adelaide now has the tightest rental market in the country, after overtaking Perth as the capital city with the lowest vacancy rate in Australia.

title.children: 'I'm a doctor ... still can't get a house': Adelaide overtakes Perth as tightest capital city rental market

image.altText: A woman with long brown hair stares directly in to a camera with a Palestinian flag behind her.

props.synopsis: Longevity has been a hallmark of the pro-Palestinian movement, with protests calling for a change in government policy held weekly since mid-October. The Jewish community and its supporters have also held regular vigils to remember those killed and taken hostage.

title.children: Six months on from the Hamas attack on Israel and war in Gaza, people in Australia are showing they haven't forgotten

image.altText: Bespectacled woman with brown hair and yellow top sitting standing in front of new smart power meter

props.synopsis: Economists love them. Regulators say they make the grid more efficient. But many Australians are finding out time-of-use tariffs mean sharply higher power prices.

title.children: Anger and despair as electricity customers shifted to 'punishing' tariffs

image.altText: Image of a high waterfall in a national park

props.synopsis: Police believe the 20-year-old was bushwalking when she slipped and fell more than 100 metres into a creek at Belmore Falls in the state's Southern Highlands.

title.children: Woman's body found three days after she fell from cliff at popular NSW waterfall

image.altText: NSW Premier Chris Minns stands at press conference with Police Minister Yasmin Catley and NSW Police Commissioner Karen Webb

props.synopsis: Chris Minns announces a review into termination payouts for public servants after it was revealed $687,613 in "termination payments" has been paid to three former NSW Police chief media advisers in the past two years.

title.children: 'It's taxpayers money': Minns announces review into public servant payouts after $700K paid to former NSW police media advisors

image.altText: Anthony Albanese at a press conference.

props.synopsis: Australia's Prime Minister Anthony Albanese urges his Israeli counterpart to avoid a ground invasion of Rafah in southern Gaza, after Benjamin Netanyahu flagged a date had been set for the offensive.

title.children: Albanese urges Netanyahu to avoid Rafah invasion, questions why Gaza aid has taken so long

image.altText: An axe lying on a road that has been cordoned off by police.

props.synopsis: Paramedics found the 38-year-old with serious head injuries at Raymond Terrace early this morning. He died at the scene. A 29-year-old man has been taken into custody.

title.children: Man armed with axe dies after confrontation with man wielding Razor scooter, police allege

image.altText: A sunset over solar panels and vineyards

props.synopsis: One of Australia's largest wineries, Casella Family Brands, has installed almost 9,000 solar panels — enough to power more than 1,900 homes.

title.children: Winery using more electricity than a small town turns to solar power as industry pushes to decarbonise

image.altText: A crowd of people face a brightly lit stage with the words 'Spilt Milk' atop it.

props.synopsis: While one music festival took a profit of almost $50 million, only 56 per cent of similar events are profitable, new research from Creative Australia has found.

title.children: More than one-third of Australian music festivals are not profitable, according to new data

image.altText: water spilling out of warragamba dam after it reached full capacity due to the severe rainfall

props.synopsis: As the Hawkesbury deals with its seventh flood in 18 months, NSW minister Rose Jackson's flood mitigation idea involves reducing the city's reliance on Warragamba Dam.

title.children: Water minister floats desalinated water solution to reduce Warragamba flood risk

image.altText: A man in a grey polo shirt stands in a green field under a blue sky.

props.synopsis: A western Victorian man is accused of altering the stone arrangement believed to be 1,500 years old, but he is disputing the site's history, suggesting it is not of Aboriginal origins.

title.children: Farmer charged with harming Aboriginal heritage after stones allegedly moved from giant eel arrangement

image.altText: Photo of two mobile phones in people's hands

props.synopsis: Australians are on track for a government-issued digital ID. Most people seem relaxed, but it's the number one story on "alt social media".

title.children: Spooky theories on the big-bad-almost hack and an ugly window into the world of 'alt social media'

image.altText: A smiling young blonde woman with a drink in her hand sits in the sun.

props.synopsis: Lachlan Young, 21, has faced a packed courtroom in Ballarat. He is charged with the murder of 23-year-old Hannah McGuire, whose body was found in a burnt-out car last week.

title.children: Man accused of murdering Hannah McGuire faces court in Ballarat

image.altText: A woman smiling and taking a selfie

props.synopsis: The alleged murder of Hannah McGuire, whose body was found in a burnt-out car near Ballarat last week, reignites calls to prevent violence against women and create a culture of respect and equality.

title.children: 'We cannot continue down this path': Anger and anguish as Ballarat mourns a bright star snuffed out

image.altText: Road slippage at Megalong Road in the Megalong Valley cuts access to the area

props.synopsis: Up to 150 trapped Megalong Valley residents could have a way out by the end of the week, according to the local mayor who is hopeful a temporary road will be approved by engineers today.

title.children: 'Everyone is stressed, worried, anxious': Community trapped by landslide given hope of way out this week

image.altText: Back of grey-haired woman's head at desk with computer screen and take-away coffee cup

props.synopsis: New analysis from KPMG shows how COVID has pushed more people over 55 back into the workforce, with the retirement age steadily increasing over the past 20 years.

title.children: The average retirement age in Australia is growing. An economist explains why

image.altText: Billie Eilish with bright dyed red hair looks sternly over the tops of little john lennon glasses

props.synopsis: The young pop superstar has released details of her third studio album. But she's not too happy that the announcement didn't go as planned.

title.children: Billie Eilish announces new album. But has the surprise already been spoiled?

image.altText: A rail line with the soil washed out from under it.

props.synopsis: Residents say they are grappling with all too familiar frustrations after severe weather in New South Wales damaged the South Coast rail line and exposed insurance vulnerabilities in the region.

title.children: South Coast trains remain offline after flooding exposes railway track's fragility

image.altText: Matildas coach Tony Gustavsson scratches his head while speaking to media at a press conference

props.synopsis: Tony Gustavsson is set to field a different looking Matildas outfit in this week's friendly against Mexico, as the team continues to deal with injuries to a host of big-name players ahead of the Olympics.

title.children: Gustavsson seeking 'answers' as injuries threaten to derail Olympic dream

image.altText: A wide angle shot of Risdon Prison in Tasmania.

props.synopsis: A Tasmanian prisoner who committed a number of animal cruelty offences, including killing juvenile sparrows, while behind bars could potentially face more jail time.

title.children: Cruelty to birds could land Tasmanian inmate more jail time

image.altText: A middle-aged man with receding hair and beard, wearing a singlet and glasses.

props.synopsis: Aliyawar Yawari had been charged with two counts of indecently assaulting a female guest at an Adelaide motel, however the charges will no longer proceed.

title.children: Indecent assault charges withdrawn against former immigration detainee
